Let’s talk about anxiety….

I was up with Ev all night with a high fever. I wasn’t surprised when he started to get sick because Marshal had just been sick over the weekend. 

As I stayed up with Ev checking his temp I started to get horrible flashbacks of doing the same with Justin. I felt the fear rush into my chest as I remembered how terrifying it was to see that high number on the thermometer. 

When Justin got a high fever that almost always meant a visit to the ER which was always followed by bad news. The tumor has grown, the chemo isn’t working, you will need to be admitted into the hospital. 

Anything related to health is such a trigger to me. I saw a perfectly healthy 24 year old complain about chest pain to find out he had cancer and then die. It’s hard to not let my mind jump to worse case scenario after what I have been through. 

So when my kids get sick, the irrational thinking begins and it starts to consume me. 
It’s hard being alone all the time because I can’t pull myself out. Justin use to be my anchor and would help bring me back to reality. 

It can be exhausting always thinking this way. 😞 I hate anxiety 😭

It was really hard going from living with my parents to then living on my own with the boys. I was terrified of sleeping alone at night. Managing a home. Single parenting. Being alone. 

I find it hard when people say “you’re so strong” like I have some choice in the matter. The way I see it, it’s ether be strong or give up” I don’t see much of a choice. I made a choice to be strong, but that doesn’t mean it isn’t hard and I don’t struggle. It’s the hardest thing I’ve done since Justin has passed away. I’m still struggling, but I keep going. That’s most important! Big milestone today! Living on my own for a year now

35 years old today! When you get older you start to ponder those deep life questions more. A question that often consumes my mind is: “How to be happy with the life I have now.” It can be hard to accept how things have turned out. I never thought I’d be a 35 year old widow and single mom of two. I’m either missing the past or grieving the future. Constantly thinking about the “what ifs”….if he was here, things would be like this.. 

So this year my focus is the present! Live in the present and focus on the little things that put a smile on my face. Fake it until you make it! I have two amazing boys to be present for and I’m so grateful for that. Hoping to find happiness in the now. I’ll let you know how it goes 😜❤️

Love coming back home to Colorado ❤️ We are spending this week with my sister and her kids in Estes Park! Having some much needed cousin time and the boys are having a blast!

I’ve been feeling a little burnt out with social media lately. Its hard to keep up with it during the summer with all the trips and fun activities going on. ❤️ So here is my photo dump of the last couple days. Thanks for following along! Means more than you know!

My best friend from college lives by my sister and it’s so fun to visit when I’m in town. My sister was able to meet new baby Sunny for the first time. 

My sweet friend @ali__wright just had her fourth child and she was born with Down syndrome. We all love her so much! She has had to use a g-tube for the last couple months and she just got news she won’t need to have it anymore and can slowly wean off of it. Yay!!!

There is so much I didn’t know about Down Syndrome that I’m now learning  through my friend. Grateful to learn more and so proud of how strong she has been through these last couple of months. I know how hard the medical world can be and can only imagine how hard it would be with a new baby. Love you @ali__wright

Sadly Justin never saw it in person, but was able to see pictures of it. He would have loved seeing the boys play on it ❤️

#treehouse #grief #griefandloss #singlemoms

We spent the last part of our Colorado trip with my cousin and his family and friends ❤️ It can be hard fitting in as a single parent. I sometimes feel like the awkward third wheel. 🤪 But after I moved to Utah my cousin welcomed me into his group of friends and they have all been so amazing in making me feel loved and welcomed. It’s meant so much to me! All of us love hanging out together and our kids get along so well, I just never thought I’d have this as a single parent. Just feel so grateful ❤️ #singleparents #singlemoms

I saw this quote and loved it! Grateful for my friends who have stood by my change through grief ❤️ I’ve really lucked out with having the best support system! 

“Grief has the power to to fundamentally and irretrievably change a person. As we learn to cope with our losses, the way we perceive things, how we act, and how we interact with others will see a gradual shift from what we used to be to the new person we’ve become. These changes are irreversible, and we must learn to accept the new version of the person we now are. Allowing the grief journey to take shape without relying on a timeline for grief and, instead, working towards healing helps us transition into this new existence and way of being.”

I’m not gonna lie Thanksgiving can be really hard for me. It was Justin’s favorite holiday because he loved to cook and eat. The ache of his absence is more profound during the holidays. 

I’ve struggled living in the now. Loving the now. Being grateful for the now. I’m ether longing for the past or grieving my future. It can be hard to get on social media on Thanksgiving and see everyone post their family pics. All I see is what I’m missing and what could have been…. it’s hard 💔 I’m on a journey of trying to love the now. That it’s okay my family looks a little different. 

So today I’m grateful for my boys because they are truly the reason I keep moving forward! I’m also grateful for my caravan community! Each and everyone of you make this journey so special. Thank you for being the heartbeat of this community, my source of strength and inspiration! Because of your incredible support, I get to be home with my boys! So thank you for being here! ❤️
